Aperture Statistics

Niklas Hausmann

13/03/2020

Introduction

This file explains how we ran the statisticla tests on the aperture size measurements. It is based on the Aps dataframe, which we created in the Basic Shell Information.R file. It is worth to redo these steps because we won’t summarise it as much this time. First, we need to source the ‘Farasan Database.R’ file through:

source('Farasan Database.R')

Then we extract the aperture measurements from the Apertures list:

Aps <- data.frame()
f <- data.frame()

for (i in 1:length(Apertures))  {
  for (j in 1:length(Apertures[[i]]))  {
    if ("Strombus.fasciatus..............Born.1778..Aperture" %in% names(Apertures[[i]][[j]]) == FALSE) {
      next
    }
    f <-
      data.frame(c(as.character(names(Apertures[i]))), c(as.character(names(Apertures[[i]][j]))), Apertures[[i]][[j]][["Strombus.fasciatus..............Born.1778..Aperture"]])
    colnames(f) <- c('Site', 'Sample', 'Aperture')
    Aps <- rbind(Aps, f)
  }
}
rm(f, i, j, Areas, Sites, Species)

To get a simple list of each measurement grouped by site and bulk sample number:

Aps[1:3,1:3]
##     Site Sample Aperture
## 1 KM1048    926    24.02
## 2 KM1048    926    18.13
## 3 KM1048    926    20.07

General aperture statistics by areas

To look at the general statistics for each areas, we added a column to Aps containing the respective bay areas and summarise the dataframe using the summarySE function:

Aps$Area <- c(rep("Khur Maadi",4122), rep("Janaba West",6171),rep("Janaba East",5169))

source("summarySE.R")

Aps_area <-summarySE(na.omit(Aps), measurevar = "Aperture", groupvars = c("Area"))
##          Area    N Aperture_mean Aperture_median       sd
## 1 Janaba East 5169      19.67116           19.60 1.483827
## 2 Janaba West 6171      21.39223           21.30 1.648272
## 3  Khur Maadi 4122      22.87554           22.85 1.821071

One-way anova

Doing an one-way analysis of variance (anova) will show whether there are statistically significant differences between the means of each bay area.

Aps_area_aov <- aov(Aperture ~ Area, data = Aps)
summary(Aps_area_aov)
##                Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)    
## Area            2  23880   11940    4415 <2e-16 ***
## Residuals   15459  41808       3                   
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Post-hoc tukey test

We then applied a post-hoc tukey test, to understand between which areas the statistically significant differences lie.

TukeyHSD(Aps_area_aov)
##   Tukey multiple comparisons of means
##     95% family-wise confidence level

General aperture statistics by sites

To do the same tests between sites, we have to take similar steps, only this time we are also using the Site column to group aperture measurements.

##Kruskal Wallis The same data on site level reveals that there are variations in sample size, normal distributions and variance between the sites, which are all assumptions for the ANOVA test used above. We will thus switch to the non-parametric Wilcoxon rank-sum test and use the pairwise.wilcox.test() function

PW_Aps <- pairwise.wilcox.test(Aps$Aperture, Aps$Site,  p.adjust.method = "bonferroni")

Graph of size distributions by site (Fig. 6b)

Similar to the graph above, we illustrate the site differences using raincloud plots, as well as other design-related packages, such as viridis and cowplot. This time, the sites are coloured by bay area, however they are in the order of largst shells (top) to smallest shells (bottom). The general trend, however, remains and sites usually stick to their bay area.

library(ggplot2)

  )) +
    geom_flat_violin(
      position = position_nudge(x = +0.2, y = 0),

Time related changes in aperture sizes (Fig. 7)

First we will reload the Aps dataframe

Aps <- data.frame()
f <- data.frame()

for (i in 1:length(Apertures))  {
  for (j in 1:length(Apertures[[i]]))  {
    if ("Strombus.fasciatus..............Born.1778..Aperture" %in% names(Apertures[[i]][[j]]) == FALSE) {
      next
    }
    f <-
      data.frame(c(as.character(names(Apertures[i]))), c(as.character(names(Apertures[[i]][j]))), Apertures[[i]][[j]][["Strombus.fasciatus..............Born.1778..Aperture"]])
    colnames(f) <- c('Site', 'Sample', 'Aperture')
    Aps <- rbind(Aps, f)
  }
}
rm(f, i, j)

and add the Area information

Aps$Area <- c(rep("Khur Maadi",4122), rep("Janaba West",6171),rep("Janaba East",5169))

Then we will add the occupation times for each site. This step is done in the SortApsByDate.R script and essentially takes the minimum and maximum occupation period for each site and interpolates fictional dates for all bulk samples between the top and the bottom of the sample column. While this is not an ideal approach for analysing parallel changes between sites, they give us an idea of changes through time within individual sites and a rough grouping of data overall.

source('SortApsByDate.R')
##         Site Sample Aperture        Area  Year
## 10304 JE0004    676    18.45 Janaba East -4830

To better illustrate trends within the dataset, we have averaged the aperture values for each bulk sample. That said, we did take into account the variability within each sample by scaling the size of each data point in the plot depending on each sample’s variability (see further below in Fig. 7a).

source("summarySE.R")
MeanAps <- summarySE(na.omit(ApsByDate[,1:5]), measurevar = c("Aperture"), groupvars=c("Sample"))
MeanYears <- summarySE(na.omit(ApsByDate[,1:5]), measurevar = c("Year"), groupvars=c("Sample"))
MeanApsByDate <- data.frame(MeanAps[,c(1,2,3,5)], Years_mean=MeanYears[,3])

MeanApsByDate <- merge(MeanApsByDate,ApsByDate,by="Sample")
MeanApsByDate <- MeanApsByDate[,c(8,6,1,2,3,4,5)]
rm(MeanAps,MeanYears)

MeanApsByDate <- distinct(MeanApsByDate)

Figure 7a changes in time including all data

To show the changes in aperture size distribution through time, we plotted each bulk sample’s mean aperture size as a point, that was itself larger or smaller depending on the variability of sizes within the specific bulk sample. We also overlayed this plot with the smoothed line using locally estimated scatterplot smoothing (LOESS).

Fig7a <- ggplot(
  MeanApsByDate, 
  aes(x = Years_mean , y=Aperture_mean, size = sd)
) +scale_color_manual(values='steel')+
  geom_point(show.legend = TRUE, alpha = 0.4) + geom_smooth(method = "loess", span = 0.5, size = 0.5, alpha=0.1)+
  ylim(17.5,25)+ theme_bw()+ guides(size = FALSE)+ coord_flip()+theme(legend.position = c(0.8,0.3))+ylab('Mean aperture size')+xlab('Year cal BP')+
  scale_size(range = c(1.5, 6))+  ggtitle("Mollusc size change across Farasan")

Fig7b

Statistical test on trends between earlier and later periods

Categorise aperture values by earlier and later periods within

To compare changes in time, which seem to be evident in Fig. 7b, we defined Early (6500–6000 calBP) and Late (5000–4800 cal BP) periods, into which the data from ApsByDate were grouped. Lastly these groups are combined into one dataframe (Ttest.df), which will be used to extract data for a two sample t-test in each bay area.

EarlyAps <- ApsByDate[ApsByDate$Year<(-6000),]
EarlyAps <- EarlyAps[EarlyAps$Year>(-6500),]
EarlyAps$Period <- c("Early")

LateAps <- ApsByDate[ApsByDate$Year<(-4800),]
LateAps <- LateAps[LateAps$Year>(-5001),]
LateAps$Period <- c("Late")

Ttest.df <- rbind(EarlyAps,LateAps)

rm(EarlyAps,LateAps)
##         Site Sample Aperture        Area  Year Period
## 15385 JE5642   2552     18.2 Janaba East -6002  Early
## 6559  JW1807   2791     23.9 Janaba West -5000   Late

Test for changes

To test changes in time for Janaba West:

JW_Ttest.df <- subset(Ttest.df,Area=='Janaba West')
t.test(Aperture~Period, data=JW_Ttest.df, var.equal=TRUE)

  ylim(17.5,25)+ theme_bw()+ guides(size = FALSE)+ coord_flip()+theme(legend.position = c(0.8,0.3))+ylab('Mean aperture size')+xlab('Year cal BP')+
  scale_size(range = c(1.5, 6))+  ggtitle("Mollusc size change at different sites")

Fig7c

And we see that rather than a long-term decrease in size, we simply have changes in occupation of sites where shells are generally smaller.
